{"title_page": "Tupolev Tu-104", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n |name = Tu-104\n |image = File:Aeroflot Tupolev Tu-104B at Arlanda, July 1972.jpg\n |caption = [[Aeroflot]] Tupolev Tu-104B at [[Arlanda Airport]] in 1972\n}}\n{{Infobox aircraft type\n |type = [[Narrow-body aircraft|Narrow-body]] [[jet airliner]]\n |manufacturer = [[Tupolev|Tupolev OKB]]\n |designer = [[Andrei Tupolev]]\n |first flight = {{start date and age|1955|06|17|df=yes}}\n |introduced = 15 September 1956 (Aeroflot)\n |retired = 1981\n |status = Retired\n |primary user = [[Aeroflot]]\n |more users = [[Czech Airlines|\u010cSA]]\n |produced = 1956\u20131960\n |number built = 201\n |unit cost =\n |developed from = [[Tupolev Tu-16]]\n |variants with their own articles =[[Tupolev Tu-110]]<br>[[Tupolev Tu-124]]\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Aeroflot Tupolev Tu-104B at Arlanda, July 1968.jpg|thumb|[[Aeroflot]] Tupolev Tu-104B at [[Arlanda Airport]] in 1968, with drag parachute deployed.]]\n\nThe '''Tupolev Tu-104''' ([[NATO reporting name]]: '''Camel''') was a [[twinjet]] medium-range [[narrow-body aircraft|narrow-body]] [[turbojet]]-powered [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[airliner]]. It was the second to enter in regular service, behind the British [[de Havilland Comet]], and was the only [[jet airliner|jetliner]] operating in the world from 1956 to 1958, when the British jetliner was grounded due to safety matters.<ref name=\"Tu104\">{{cite web |url=http://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/libro?codigo=237370|title=Reactores Comerciales (1999a) (en: Commercial Jetliners) | isbn = 84-95088-87-8 |work=Antonio L\u00f3pez Ortega |publisher=Agualarga Editores S.l. |accessdate=2008-09-26 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957, Czechoslovak Airlines&nbsp;\u2013 \u010cSA, (now [[Czech Airlines]]) became the first airline in the world to fly a route exclusively with jet airliners, using the Tu-104A variant between Prague and Moscow. In civil service, the Tu-104 carried over 90 million passengers with Aeroflot (then the world's largest airline), and a lesser number with \u010cSA, while it also saw operation with the [[Soviet Air Force]]. Its successors included the [[Tupolev Tu-124|Tu-124]], the [[Tupolev Tu-134|Tu-134]] and the [[Tupolev Tu-154|Tu-154]].\n\n==Design and development==\nAt the beginning of the 1950s, the Soviet Union's Aeroflot airline needed a modern airliner with better capacity and performance than the piston-engined aircraft then in operation. The design request was filled by the Tupolev OKB, which based their new airliner on its [[Tupolev Tu-16|Tu-16 'Badger']] strategic bomber. The wings, engines, and tail surfaces of the Tu-16 were retained with the airliner, but the new design adopted a wider, pressurised fuselage designed to accommodate 50 passengers.  The prototype build in MMZ 'Opit' first flew on June 17, 1955 with Yu.L. Alasheyev at the controls. It was fitted with a [[drag parachute]] to shorten the landing distance by up to {{convert|400|m|ft}}, since at the time not many airports had sufficiently long runways.<ref name=Tu104/>\n\nAlthough a popular story says Westerners were surprised by the arrival of the Tu-104 in [[London]] during a 1956 state visit{{dubious|Flight 1956 p372 reports Gen Serov arriving March, Krushchev arrives April|date=November 2015}} by [[Nikolai Bulganin]] and [[Nikita Khrushchev]], the airplane had already been revealed at the July 1955 [[Tushino Airfield|Tushino]] airshow.<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/CIA-RDP61S00137A000100070006-7.pdf Analysis of Camel/Tu-104], Central Intelligence Agency, August 3, 1957.</ref>\n\nThe Tu-104 was powered by two [[Mikulin AM-3]] turbojets placed in the wing roots (resembling the configuration of the [[de Havilland Comet]]). The crew consisted of five people: two pilots, a navigator (seated in the glazed \"bomber\" nose), a flight engineer and a radio operator (later eliminated). The airplane raised great curiosity by its lavish \"Victorian\" interior&nbsp;\u2013 so-called by some Western-hemisphere observers&nbsp;\u2013 due to the materials used: [[mahogany]], [[copper]] and [[lace]].<ref name=Tu104/>\n\nTu-104 pilots were trained on the [[Ilyushin Il-28|Il-28]] bomber, followed by mail flights on an unarmed Tu-16 bomber painted in Aeroflot colors, between [[Moscow]] and [[Yekaterinburg|Sverdlovsk]]. Pilots with previous Tu-16 experience transitioned into the Tu-104 with relative ease. The Tu-104 was considered difficult to fly, as it was heavy on controls and quite fast on final approach, and at low speeds it would display a tendency to stall, a feature common with highly-swept wings.\nExperience with the Tu-104 led the Tupolev Design Bureau to develop the world's first turbofan series-built airliner, the [[Tupolev Tu-124]], designed for local markets, and subsequently the more commercially successful [[Tupolev Tu-134|Tu-134]].\n\n==Operational history==\n[[File:Tupolev TU-104A Czech Airlines (CSA), LKKB Kbely, Czech Republic PP1185955612.jpg|thumb|Czechoslovak Airlines Tu-104A at [[Kbely Aviation Museum]], Prague]]\nOn 15 September 1956, the Tu-104 began revenue service on Aeroflot's [[Moscow]]-[[Omsk]]-[[Irkutsk]] route, replacing the [[Ilyushin Il-14]]. The flight time was reduced from 13 hours and 50 minutes to 7 hours and 40 minutes, and the new jet dramatically increased the level of passenger comfort.<ref name=Tu104/> By 1957, Aeroflot had placed the Tu-104 in service on routes from [[Vnukovo Airport]] in Moscow to [[London]], [[Budapest]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Beijing]], [[Brussels]], [[Ottawa]], [[Delhi]], and [[Prague]].\n\nIn 1957, [[Czech Airlines|\u010cSA Czechoslovak Airlines]] became the only export customer for the Tu-104, placing the aircraft on routes to [[Moscow]], [[Paris]], and [[Brussels]]. \u010cSA bought six Tu-104As (four new and two used examples) configured for 81 passengers. Three of these aircraft were subsequently written off (one due to a refueling incident in India and another to a pilot error without fatalities).<ref name=Tu104/>\n\nIn 1959 a Tu-104 was leased to Sir Henry Lunn Ltd. ([[Lunn Poly]]) of London which used the aircraft to transport holiday-makers to Russia with a 4.5 hour flight time.\n\nWhilst the Tu-104 continued to be used by Aeroflot throughout the 1960s and 1970s, the safety record of the aircraft was poor, in comparison to other jet airliners of its day (16 out of 96 aircraft were lost in crashes). The Tu-104 was unreliable, heavy, very unstable with poor control response, with an inclination to [[Dutch roll]]. Poor design aerodynamics of the wings resulted in a propensity to stall with little or no warning and a dangerous tendency to pitch-up violently before stalling and entering an irrecoverable dive. Due to the fear of inadvertent stalls aircrew would fly approaches above the recommended approach speed, landing at {{convert|270|-|300|km/h|abbr=on}}, nearly {{convert|50|km/h|abbr=on}} faster. At least 2 accidents were attributed to the pitch-up phenomenon, prompting changes to the design of the aircraft and operating procedures, but the problem remained. Aeroflot retired the Tu-104 from civil service in March 1979 following a fatal accident at Moscow, but several aircraft were transferred to the Soviet military, which used them as staff transports and to train [[cosmonaut]]s in [[Vomit Comet|zero gravity]]. After a military Tu-104 crash in February 1981 killed 52 people (17 were senior army and naval staff), the type was permanently removed from service. The last flight of the Tu-104 was a ferry flight to [[Ulyanovsk Aircraft Museum]] in 1986.\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Tupolev Tu-104 near Vnukovo Airport - Moscow.JPG|thumb|right|A Tu-104 statue near [[Vnukovo Airport]]]]\n[[File:Tu104 Monino.jpg|thumb|\u0422u-104 preserved at [[Monino]] museum. This aircraft was used to train cosmonauts.]]\n''Data from:'' <ref name=Tu104/>\n\n* '''Tu-104''' \u2013 initial version seating 50 passengers. It used two Mikulin AM-3 turbojet engines, each with {{convert|6,735|kg}} of thrust. 29 airframes were built.\n* '''Tu-104 2NK-8''' \u2013 Proposed version powered by two [[Kuznetsov NK-8]] turbofan engines.\n* '''Tu-104A''' \u2013 Improved version appearing in June 1957; continued improvements of the Mikulin engines (Mikulin AM-3M each with {{convert|8,700|kg}} of thrust) permitted significant growth in capacity, resulting in a 70-seater variant. The Tu-104A became the definitive production variant. On 6 September 1957, it flew with 20 t of payload at {{convert|11,211|m}} of altitude. On 24 September 1957, it reached {{convert|970.8|km/h|abbr=on}} average speed with a two tonne payload. A total of 80 airframes were built, of which six were exported to Czechoslovakia.\n* '''Tu-104AK'''&nbsp;\u2013 [[testbed aircraft]] for Zero-G cosmonauts' training and testing the Soviet space programme equipment\n* '''Tu-104A-TS''' \u2013 Five Tu-104A's converted to freighter/medevac aircraft.\n* '''Tu-104B''' \u2013 Further improvements made by stretching fuselage {{convert|1.2|m}} and fitting new Mikulin AM-3M-500 turbojets ({{convert|9,700|kg}} of thrust each). The Tu-104B was able to accommodate 100 passengers. This variant took advantage of the newer fuselage from the Tu-110 and the existing wings. It began revenue service with Aeroflot on 15 April 1959 on the Moscow-Saint Petersburg route. A total of 95 airframes were built. Most were later rebuilt to Tu-104V-115 standard.\n* '''Tu-104B-TS''' \u2013 Six Tu-104B's converted to freighter/medevac aircraft.\n* '''Tu-104D''' \u2013 VIP version with two sleeper cabins forward and a 39-seat cabin aft.\n* '''Tu-104D-85''' \u2013 Tu-104A airframes rebuilt to accommodate 85 passengers.\n* '''Tu-104D 3NK-8''' \u2013 Project powered by three NK-8 engines, precursor of Tu-154.\n* '''Tu-104E''' \u2013 A higher performance Tu-104 powered by RD-16-15 engines giving better fuel economy and greater thrust. Two prototypes were converted from Tu-104B's CCCP-42441 and CCCP-42443. The program was cancelled in the mid-1960s in favor of the [[Tu-154]].\n* '''Tu-104G''' \u2013 VIP version for the Federal government with two VIP cabins forward and a 54-seat cabin aft.\n* '''Tu-104LL'''&nbsp;\u2013 Several serial numbers converted for use in testing Tu-129, Tu-22M electronics, and air-to-air missile systems (including launch).\n* '''Tu-104SH''' \u2013 Navigator trainer in two versions\n* '''Tu-104V''' \u2013 The first use of this designation was for a projected 117 seat medium haul version with six-abreast seating. Project cancelled.\n* '''Tu-104V''' \u2013 The second use of this designation was used for Tu-104A airframes rebuilt to accommodate 100/105 passengers. A later version packed 115 passengers in by reducing seat pitch and adding seat rows.\n*'''Tu-104V-115''' \u2013 Tu-104B airframes rebuilt to accommodate 115 passengers, with new radio and navigational equipment.\n* '''[[Tupolev Tu-107|Tu-107]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Proposed military transport version with rear loading ramp and defensive turret armed with paired cannon. One prototype built; project cancelled\n* '''[[Tu-110]]''' \u2013 Four-engined version intended for export. A number of prototypes were built. Project cancelled.\n* '''Tu-118''' \u2013 A projected turboprop freighter version powered by four [[Kuznetsov TV-2F]] engines.\n\n==Former operators==\n[[File:CSA Tu-104A OK-LDC ARN May 1971.png|thumb|[[Czech Airlines|CSA Czechoslovak Airlines]] Tupolev Tu-104A at [[Arlanda Airport]] in 1971.]]\n;{{flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n* [[Czech Airlines|CSA Czechoslovak Airlines]] \u2013 Six aircraft.\n* [[Czechoslovakian Air Force]]\n;{{MNG}}\n* [[Military of Mongolia]]\n;{{USSR}}\n* [[Aeroflot]]\n* [[Soviet Air Force]]\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n[[File:Tu-104 Crash site near Nicosia airport.jpg|thumb|Wreckage of the Czechoslovak Airlines Tupolev Tu-104 (OK-MDE) near Nicosia airport (2015)]]\n\nAccording to the American [[Flight Safety Foundation]], between 1958 and 1981, 16 Tu-104s were lost in crashes out of 37 aircraft written off (hull loss rate = 18%) with a total of 1140 fatalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/types/Tupolev-104/statistics|title=Aviation Safety Network > ASN Aviation Safety Database > Aircraft type index > Tupolev Tu-104 > Tupolev Tu-104 Statistics|first=Harro|last=Ranter|date=|website=aviation-safety.net|accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style= \"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:100px;\"|Date \n! style=\"width:75px;\"|Tail number \n! style=\"width:70px;\"|Aircraft type\n! style=\"width:125px;\"|Location \n!width=\"50\"|Casualties\n! style=\"width:600px;\"|Description\n!width=\"25\"|Refs\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1958|02|19}}\n|align=center|CCCP-\u041b5414 \n|align=center|Tu-104\n|{{flagicon|USSR}}[[Savasleyka (air base)|Savasleyka]] \n|align=center|{{nts|0}}/3\n|Force-landed short of the runway after running out of fuel following a diversion.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= CCCP-L5414|id= 19580219-0|accessdate= 2015-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|{{dts|format=dmy|1958|08|15}}\n|align=center|CCCP-\u041b5442 \n|align=center|Tu-104A\n|{{flagicon|USSR}}[[Chita, Zabaykalsky Krai|Chita]] \n|align=center|{{nts|64}}/64\n|'''[[Aeroflot Flight 4]]''' stalled, spun down and crashed after entering an updraft at {{convert|12000|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n|align=center|<ref>{{ASN accident|title= CCCP-L5442|id= 19580815-3|accessdate= 2015-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.airdisaster.ru/database.php?id=239|title= \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 \u0422\u0443-104\u0410 \u041c\u0423\u0422\u0410 \u0413\u0412\u0424 \u0432 215 \u043a\u043c \u043e\u0442 \u0430/\u043f \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a|language= Russian|trans-title= Accident Tu-104 215 km from Khabarovsk Airport|publisher= airdisaster.ru|